webpackJsonp([0xb2d55d5c525],{1002:function(a,t){a.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Justin Ball",author:"Justin Ball"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/Users/jbasdf/projects/justinball/src/posts/2008-06-07-ajax-calls-using-jquery-in-ruby-on-rails/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>jQuery is the hot javascript library and it is small and it is cooler than Prototype, the default library that comes with Ruby on Rails.  Ergo I plugged it in and pulled out everything else.  The ajax calls are very simple and look like this:</p>\n<pre><code class="javascript">\n$.post("function_name",{ key:value } ,function(data)\n{\n  // do stuff with data\n});\n</pre></code>\n<p>The problem is that you will start seeing \'ActionController::InvalidAuthenticityToken\' and your ajax calls will fail.</p>\n<p><a href="http://henrik.nyh.se/2008/05/rails-authenticity-token-with-jquery">Here is a very elegant solution</a>.</p>',frontmatter:{title:"Ajax calls using jQuery in Ruby on Rails",date:"June 07, 2008",imageUrl:null,image:null}}},pathContext:{path:"/ajax-calls-using-jquery-in-ruby-on-rails"}}}});
